editor_inbox.text: The extraction pipeline failed—we're running blind on that piece. Have Detective flag it as incomplete until we get a clean pull; I won't publish a story where half the details are missing. What's the blocker on architecturaldig61losa?

Six issues we missed on the first pass—that's sloppy work, but Scout caught it before print. Run them through fact-check and layout tonight; we don't republish incomplete archives. This is exactly why we verify twice.

Courier's running a 50% failure rate — mid-2000s archive.org is a dead zone. Detective idle with 284 unchecked names gathering dust. Three re-extractions finally queued for the July 2015, November 2015, and October 2019 disasters. I need you to tell me where to find PDFs that archive.org doesn't have, and whether to turn the Detective loose on the full backlog.

Pipeline's running but burning fuel on dead ends. Courier keeps hitting the AD Archive wall — every Bondi viewer URL is a wasted cycle. I've queued three re-extractions that should have been done five cycles ago. Detective's grinding through names at 21%. Your call on the AD Archive problem and the Designer mode switch.

Detective broke the stall — 77 names checked, up from 19. Henri Samuel still our only match. Cleaned three garbage entries from the database. July and November 2015 re-extractions queued for the fourth time — if they don't process this cycle, I'm going to find out why personally. AD Archive downloads remain dead in the water. Need your call on whether to pursue those 1989-93 issues or cut our losses.

Good. Run those names against the secondary sources we flagged — flight manifests, property records, charitable donations to his foundations. Clearing one database means nothing; we need to know if there's a story underneath the surface. Send me what you find by end of day.

Scout found six technical debts we should've caught in the first pass—that's on us, not them. We'll clean those out by end of week and tighten QA before the next deploy, but this is exactly why we don't ship until it's right.

Pipeline's running but bleeding efficiency. Reader keeps crashing into the same brick wall — expanded the blacklist to 14 dead PDFs. Courier's still trying to download from a site that doesn't serve downloads. Detective's at 21% cross-referenced. I need a decision on the AD Archive URLs and whether you want the Designer switched to creating mode.

Two names vetted against the records—clean. We move forward on both, but tell your source we're running the other twelve regardless. Standard procedure: we verify everything ourselves, we don't outsource our due diligence to anyone, not even the Feds.

Detective's burning daylight — 284 names unchecked, and it just spent a cycle cross-referencing placeholder names I already killed. That's not a bottleneck, that's a blockage. Meanwhile the Reader's caught up and the Researcher hasn't built a single dossier in 158 cycles. The pipeline's top-heavy with data and starved for analysis. I need a decision on the Detective's throughput and the Designer's mode switch.

Good catch by Scout — that's the kind of work that separates us from the blogs. Get those documented and prioritized by severity; I want to know which ones break the user experience and which ones are just noise. We move on the critical ones this week.

Detective's the bottleneck and it's choking everything downstream. 284 names unchecked, Researcher idle for 158 cycles. I've blacklisted the pre-1960 scans that were burning Reader cycles, queued two overdue re-extractions. Need to talk about speeding up cross-referencing — at this pace we're looking at 57 more cycles to clear the queue.
Clean sweep on the names, which means we're not sitting on anything. Tell the detective to widen the net—six isn't a story, it's a starting position. We run this properly or we don't run it at all.

Detective's checked 19 names out of 364. At current pace, we finish cross-referencing sometime next century. That's not a bottleneck — that's a roadblock. Meanwhile the Reader's burning cycles on another dead scan and the Researcher's been idle for 157 cycles waiting for leads that aren't coming. I need you to look at Detective throughput — batch size, parallelization, something. The investigation can't proceed if we can't check names.

Good leg work on the vetting, but negative results aren't news—they're just baseline due diligence. What we need: who *requested* those checks and why those six names specifically. That's the actual story. Get me the paper trail.

Two pieces is thin, but if there's overlap with our existing database, Detective will find the thread. Architecture digest leads usually pan out—those homeowners tend to be repeat subjects. Let me know what cross-reference flags.

Detective's the story and it's not a good one. Twelve cycles at 5% — 287 names sitting unchecked while the Researcher collects dust. Everything upstream is running clean. I need you to look at what's throttling the Detective before we drown in unprocessed data.

Scout caught what our automation missed—that's the second gap this month. Have her document the pattern and send it to tech; if archive.org's changing their headers, we need to know before it hits us again. We're running a follow-up piece on digital preservation, so this actually works.

The extraction pipeline failed on that piece — either the source material was thin or we didn't calibrate the parser correctly. Get with Detective on what they see in the cross-reference, but meanwhile I need you running that file back through manually. We don't publish gaps.

Good. That's the baseline work—now we need teeth on it. Make sure Detective isn't just pattern-matching; I want him cross-referencing against the three prior stories in the archive to flag any contradictions or new angles we missed the first time through. If those six features hold up clean, we've got something to run with.
